Take advantage of SCOE's FREE Construction Training Boot Camp!
Starts: Monday, September 21 through November 2, 20202
Monday - Wednesday 7:30 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
To Enroll visit us at 1310 "I" Street in Modesto.

Earn industry recognized certifications in Photovoltics (Solar Panel Installation/Removal), Hazwoper (Hazardous Waste Operations and Emergency Management), and OSHA (Occupational Safety and Health Administration).
For more information, call (209) 575-3450 or (209) 534-5989 or register in person for this career training opportunity.
Open seats are limited!

Join the Scavenger Hunt!
No groups or gathering? No problem! Join the no-contact Scavenger Hunt. Head out by foot or by bike into your community to see how many items you can find from their list, share your photos, and be entered to win a prize! To sign up or learn more, https://www.walkandrollstanislaus.com/scavenger-hunt

Walk & Roll Stanislaus is a regional bicyclist and pedestrian safety and education campaign in Stanislaus County. The Stanislaus Council of Governments (StanCOG) is teaming up with community leaders and advocates to improve road safety, increase awareness of and empathy toward active transportation users, and boost walking and bicycling rates throughout the county.
#walkandrollstanislaus

Character strengths are the positive qualities individuals have—as reflected in their thoughts, feelings, and actions—that promote the well-being of themselves and others. Did you know...
1. Character strengths help make kids happier
2. Character strengths promote better psychological health
3. Kids with character strengths get along better with peers
4. Character strengths increase academic adjustments and success
Learn more at https://ggie.berkeley.edu/student-well-being/character-strengths-for-students/#tab__2

Are you looking to start your Tech Education?
Check out this FREE 7-Month Code Academy that can set you on your way to a career in technology!
Bay Valley Tech’s code academy program prepares students for tech careers in less time than traditional four-year universities.
Web development curriculum includes HTML/CSS, Bootstrap, JavaScript, TypeScript, Angular, SCSS, Node.js, Mongo DB, MySQL
Flexible online lessons with weekly in-person classes and community-based learning provide lots of support, peer study groups, and mentorship from professional software developers
Approximately 20 hours per week of study time for 7-months (slower-paced options available for students working full-time)
Students must be at least 18 years old to participate.
Prior programming experience is helpful but not necessary.
Applicants must complete prerequisite self-study materials and assessments before acceptance into the code academy.
Start Your Tech Career Today! FREE 7-Month Code Academy
THREE MORE CLASSES AVAILABLE IN 2020
Apply at www.bayvalleytech.com/code-academy-application

post_text:
Looking to BUILD new skills for the Construction Industry?

Check out this FREE 6-Month Construction Technology Program and find a career!
A building trade’s pre-apprenticeship program that helps prepare individuals for entry into the various construction trades apprenticeships.
We provide tools, as well as remedial education, and resources to receive a high school diploma.
The primary goal is placement in a construction apprenticeship training program.
The Construction Technology Program is a job preparation program, offered to both men and women 18 years and older, and includes both classroom instruction and hands-on mock-up building practice.
Industry Certifications boot camps available!
Learn more at https://www.stancoe.org/division/northern-california-construction-training-ncct

Are you looking for a new career opportunity?
According to the Partnerships for Industry and Education, VOLT Institute is one of California’s TOP 3 programs and recognized at the 2019 California Economic Summit.
In the 8-month Industrial Maintenance Mechanic program, you will learn what you need to know to keep manufacturing facilities up and running.
*Hands-on instruction.
*Small class size.
*Work locally.
*High wages.
*Job security.
With 96% job placement assistance, the VOLT Institute can help launch your career in local manufacturing.
Learn more about this program and other VOLT Institute training at www.VOLTInstitute.com

Open position for a Network Systems Technician I at SCOE.
Check it out on Edjoin @ https://www.edjoin.org/Home/DistrictJobPosting/1305553 Please note that applications are only accepted via EdJoin.
Overview: Will perform a variety of technical and resource services in the installation, operation, repair, maintenance, and diagnosis of technology and provide technical user support assistance.

EDUCATION AND EXPERIENCE: Any combination equivalent to two years of college-level course work in computer science and two years experience in networked computer installations, operations, troubleshooting, and repair work. A+ certification or evidence of equivalent skill level desired.

Most recently Patterson Joint Unified School District has joined with SCOE and other local companies as we strive to bring even more FREE software development training programs to Stanislaus County. StanEmergency
May 20 at 1:09 PM ·

Effective today the State of California has approved our county variance application. This new state approval will allow for our county to move forward into an expanded stage 2 with modifications such as:

▪️Destination retail (retail stores), including shopping malls and swap meets
▪️Dine-in restaurants (other amenities, like bars or gaming areas, are not permitted in Stage 2)

The opening of schools for in-person learning will be delayed, as more planning still needs to take place. The Public Health Officer engaged in discussions with local Superintendents beginning in March and continues the collaborative process to assess and plan.

➡️ To learn more about the new county variance attestation visit the California Department of Public Health at: https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CID/DCDC/Pages/COVID-19/County_Variance_Attestation_Form.aspx

➡️ For the latest Stanislaus County COVID-19 information visit: www.StanEmergency.com

post_text:
Each year during the month of May, we take the time to thank SCOE teachers, classified staff, and administrators for everything they do throughout the year to support students and families in Stanislaus County.
This year, more than ever, we owe a ton of gratitude and appreciation to our staff who had to learn to work remotely in a matter of days due to this pandemic.
Thank you to our teachers and credentialed staff for embracing distance-learning and zoom classrooms to ensure our students continue to have quality instruction. And, thank you to our classified staff who are keeping our essential services up and running so we can continue to support districts and families.
#WeAreStanCOE

Thank you to our teachers and credentialed staff for embracing distance-learning and zoom classrooms to ensure our students continue to have quality instruction. And, thank you to our classified staff who are keeping our essential services up and running so we can continue to support districts and families.

post_text: With people all over the world worried about the pandemic, practicing "Stay-at-home" distancing, and unsure about the future, this is the time to focus on mental health. Create a daily routine that consists of things that make you happy and avoid things that can trigger stress. Some people enjoy relaxation, exercise, and checking in with friends and family via Facetime, Tango, or other video conferencing. Each individual is different. Check in with yourself and figure out what works best for you.

post_text:
Renowned middle school teacher Steve Isaacs offers up some of the best ways to keep students engaged and connected during COVID-19 ... by giving them something they enjoy…Minecraft.
There are currently 6 Minecraft challenges that can be done at home and even allow students to connect during the current situation with Covid-19. http://www.flipgrid.com/minecraftcovid19.
The challenges include:
1. Minecraft Stuck at Home Challenge - Build your dream home for the duration of the social distancing.
2. What is Covid-19? – Build a model of the virus.
3. Future Medical Facility - Design and build a medical facility that can handle the challenges we are facing.
4. Inform the Public - Design a library or museum to share information about the virus and dispel misinformation.
5. Escape / ENTRY Room - Design an escape room full of challenges that allows the player to enter the restroom to wash their hands.
6. Covid-19 Rube Goldberg Machine - Create a Rube Goldberg Machine that provides a complex device to solve a simple problem related to Covid-19.

post_text:
Schools in Stanislaus County originally said the earliest students could return to school would be May 4. Schools now have further guidance and directives from State Superintendent of Instruction Tony Thurmond and Governor Gavin Newsom to keep school facilities closed through the end of the current school year.

With this new information and an abundance of caution, the Stanislaus County Office of Education and school district superintendents are taking a safety-first approach and immediate action to extend the school facility closures through the end of the school year. “We want students and parents to understand that the 2019-20 school year is not over; it has just transitioned from classroom instruction to distance learning,” said Stanislaus County Superintendent of Schools Scott Kuykendall.

In the coming days and weeks, districts will provide their families with information regarding graduation, grades and transcripts, scholarships, summer school, and continued distance learning instruction.

In an effort to prevent the spread of COVID-19, the Stanislaus County Office of Education, in collaboration with the 25 school districts in the county, announced plans for school closures beginning Thursday, March 19. Return dates will be announced by individual school districts.
Local superintendents did not make this decision lightly and recognize that this may cause a hardship for some families. The decision was made based on declining student attendance, increased health concerns, and community feedback.

post_text:
COVID-19 Update March 13
With the guidance of Public Health, all public schools in Stanislaus County will remain open at this time. We recognize that this is an ever-changing situation and will continue to make decisions to keep schools open as long as we believe it is safe for students and staff members.

Even as we see colleges canceling classes, moving to distance learning, major sporting events and other large events being cancelled, or postponed, our public health doctors still recommend that our schools stay open. If a case of COVID-19 is confirmed, for either a student or a staff member, we will consult with the Stanislaus County Public Health Department to determine whether school closure is recommended, and for what length of time.

Santos is continuing his education at UC Berkeley and excited to also receive a scholarship from the University. Congratulations to all the students in Stanislaus County who are going above and beyond!

The 36th Annual High School Mock Trial Competition final trial and awards were held on February 18. Congratulations to the winning team from Gregori High School!
Other competition results...
Runner-up team - - Turlock High School
Journalism Contest winner- - Rana Banankhah, Modesto High School
Artist in the Courtroom winner - - Azrael Post, Johansen High School
Spirit of Stanislaus County Mock Trial Award & Scholarship winner - - Breanna Donnelly, Modesto High School
Ryan Dickerson Award for Excellence & Leadership in Mock Trial winner - - Brian Hill, Hughson High School

Gregori will represent Stanislaus County at the State Mock Trial in Los Angeles, March 20-22, 2020.
